  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>LinkedIn Ads</strong> is a self-serve advertising platform enabling businesses to run paid campaigns targeting professionals by job title, company size, industry, skills, and seniority level. According to LinkedIn's own data, 4 out of 5 LinkedIn members drive business decisions, making the platform the primary channel for B2B paid media despite average CPCs of $5-$15 — 2-5x higher than Facebook or Google.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Average CPC</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$5-$15</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Paid Advertising</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Average B2B CPL</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$50-$150</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Minimum daily budget</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$10/day</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">LinkedIn is the only platform where you can target "VP of Marketing at SaaS companies with 50-200 employees in North America" and reliably reach that exact person. That precision makes it the default B2B paid channel for companies where a single won deal justifies thousands in ad spend.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are LinkedIn Ads?</h2>
        <p>LinkedIn Ads is the paid advertising product within LinkedIn Campaign Manager — LinkedIn's self-serve ad platform. It sits within the broader LinkedIn ecosystem of 950 million+ members, the majority of whom use the platform in a professional context: researching vendors, consuming industry content, and making purchase decisions.</p>
        <p>The fundamental advantage over other ad networks is the depth and accuracy of professional targeting data. LinkedIn members self-report their job title, employer, industry, seniority, and skills as part of maintaining their professional profile. That data — unlike the behavioural inferences Meta and Google use — is accurate by design: people have direct incentives to keep their LinkedIn profiles current.</p>
        <p>LinkedIn Ads objectives map to the standard B2B funnel:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Awareness:</strong> Brand awareness, video views — reach your ideal customer profile with messaging</li>
          <li><strong>Consideration:</strong> Website visits, engagement, video views — drive qualified traffic and content consumption</li>
          <li><strong>Conversion:</strong> Lead generation, website conversions, job applicants — capture demand and measure pipeline</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">LinkedIn's reach among decision-makers</div>
          <p>LinkedIn data shows <strong>4 out of 5 members drive business decisions</strong>. For B2B marketers, this is the core argument for the platform: the audience is pre-qualified by profession. On Facebook or Instagram, reaching a VP of Finance requires complex audience construction and behavioural inference. On LinkedIn, it is a targeting dropdown.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why LinkedIn Ads matter for B2B marketing</h2>
        <p>LinkedIn Ads earns its place in the B2B media mix for four specific reasons:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Unmatched professional targeting precision.</strong> Filter by job title, company name, company size, industry, seniority, years of experience, member skills, and degree. Layer these to reach exact roles at exact companies — something impossible on any other ad platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Higher intent from a professional mindset.</strong> LinkedIn users browse in a professional context. An ad for a B2B SaaS tool interrupts someone reading industry content — not someone watching pet videos. Receptiveness to business messaging is significantly higher than on social-first platforms.</li>
          <li><strong>Account-based marketing (ABM) at scale.</strong> Upload a list of 500 target companies and LinkedIn matches them to member profiles. Run campaigns exclusively to employees at your named accounts — a targeting capability no other platform matches for ABM.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead Gen Forms reduce friction dramatically.</strong> LinkedIn pre-fills form fields with members' profile data. Instead of clicking through to a landing page form (and abandoning), members submit leads without leaving LinkedIn. This typically triples conversion rates vs. traffic-to-landing-page campaigns.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How LinkedIn Ads work</h2>
        <p>Campaigns are created and managed in LinkedIn Campaign Manager. The workflow has four phases: objective, audience, format, and budget.</p>

        <h3>Phase 1 — Objective selection</h3>
        <p>Choose from awareness (brand visibility), consideration (engagement, website visits), or conversion (lead gen, website conversions). The objective determines which bidding options and ad formats are available.</p>

        <h3>Phase 2 — Audience targeting</h3>
        <p>Layer criteria to build a precise audience. LinkedIn recommends targeting audiences of 50,000-300,000 for sponsored content campaigns (larger for awareness, tighter for conversions). Available parameters:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Job title, job function, seniority level</li>
          <li>Company name, company size, industry, company growth rate</li>
          <li>Member skills, years of experience, degrees and fields of study</li>
          <li>Geography (country, region, city-level)</li>
          <li>Matched audiences: upload company lists, contact lists, or retarget website visitors via LinkedIn Insight Tag</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase 3 — Ad format selection</h3>
        <p>LinkedIn offers six main ad formats:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Single image (Sponsored Content):</strong> Native feed ad with image, headline, and CTA — the most widely used format</li>
          <li><strong>Video:</strong> Autoplay in the feed — highest engagement rate; effective for product demos and thought leadership</li>
          <li><strong>Carousel:</strong> Multiple image/headline cards — good for multi-product campaigns or step-by-step storytelling</li>
          <li><strong>Lead Gen Form:</strong> Native form attached to a sponsored content ad — highest conversion rate of any format</li>
          <li><strong>Message Ad:</strong> Direct to LinkedIn Inbox — high open rates but lower scale; works for ABM personalisation</li>
          <li><strong>Text Ad (right rail):</strong> Small display ads in desktop right column — lowest cost but lowest engagement</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase 4 — Bidding and budget</h3>
        <p>LinkedIn uses an auction system. Set a daily or total campaign budget and choose a bid strategy:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Maximum delivery:</strong> LinkedIn optimises for most results within budget (good for new campaigns)</li>
          <li><strong>Cost cap:</strong> Set a target CPC or CPL ceiling — LinkedIn bids to stay at or below it</li>
          <li><strong>Manual bidding:</strong> Set your max CPC directly; gives full control but requires active management</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">LinkedIn Ads vs other B2B paid channels</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Channel</th><th>Targeting basis</th><th>Avg. B2B CPL</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
