        <h2 id="examples">Real LinkedIn Ads examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — SaaS company targeting VPs</h3>
        <p>A project management SaaS ran sponsored content targeting VP-level marketers at companies with 100+ employees in North America. Budget: $3,000/month. Ad offered a free 14-day trial with a short video of the product. Results: 40 demo requests at $75 per lead. With an average contract value of $15,000/year, the campaign generated a 5x return on ad spend in closed revenue within 90 days.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — staffing agency using Lead Gen Forms</h3>
        <p>A staffing agency ran Lead Gen Form ads offering a "2026 Salary Guide" PDF to HR Directors and Talent Acquisition Managers. The in-app form pre-filled name, email, and company from LinkedIn profiles. Result: 200 leads per month at an average cost of $28 per lead — far below the industry average. Of those leads, 15% converted to discovery calls within 30 days.</p>

        <h3>Example 3 — ABM campaign for enterprise software</h3>
        <p>An enterprise software vendor uploaded a list of 300 target accounts to LinkedIn Matched Audiences. They ran a sequence of three ads over 60 days: a thought leadership article, a customer case study, and a limited-time demo offer. Targeting was so narrow that average frequency reached 12 impressions per member. The campaign generated 18 sales-qualified meetings from the 300-account list — a 6% meeting rate from cold outreach.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">LinkedIn Ads vs organic LinkedIn content — which to prioritise?</h2>
        <p>Both have a role in a B2B LinkedIn strategy. The choice depends on timeline and budget.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>LinkedIn Ads (paid)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Immediate reach to your exact target audience</li>
              <li>Precise control over who sees what message</li>
              <li>Scales with budget — more spend, more reach</li>
              <li>Results visible within days</li>
              <li>Best for campaigns, launches, and pipeline acceleration</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Organic LinkedIn content</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>No direct cost — only time investment</li>
              <li>Builds brand authority and credibility over time</li>
              <li>Organic reach is limited but compounds through engagement</li>
              <li>Takes 3-6 months to build meaningful audience</li>
              <li>Best for thought leadership and long-term inbound</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for LinkedIn Ads</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start narrow, then scale.</strong> Begin with a tight audience — a specific job title in a specific geography. Prove the campaign converts before expanding targeting. Broad audiences on LinkedIn burn budget fast because the CPCs are high.</li>
          <li><strong>Use Lead Gen Forms over landing pages for conversions.</strong> LinkedIn Lead Gen Forms consistently achieve 10-13% conversion rates vs 2-5% for landing page traffic from LinkedIn. Unless you need the landing page session data for attribution, Lead Gen Forms win.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the offer to the funnel stage.</strong> Cold audiences respond to educational content and soft CTAs ("Download our guide"). Retargeting audiences — people who visited your site — respond to demo offers and free trials. Mixing these up wastes budget.</li>
          <li><strong>Test creative every 4-6 weeks.</strong> LinkedIn audiences are small. Once a campaign reaches high frequency (4+ impressions per member), engagement drops sharply. Refresh ad creative regularly to maintain performance.</li>
          <li><strong>Install the LinkedIn Insight Tag on your website.</strong> This enables website retargeting, conversion tracking, and demographic reporting on who visits your site. It is essential for any serious LinkedIn Ads programme — set it up before launching your first campaign.</li>
          <li><strong>Benchmark cost per qualified lead, not cost per click.</strong> LinkedIn CPCs look expensive vs other platforms. The relevant metric is cost per sales-qualified lead (or cost per pipeline). A $120 CPL that converts to a $20,000 deal is efficient; a $30 CPL that converts to nothing is not.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — targeting too broadly to save on CPCs</div>
          <p>When LinkedIn Ads feel expensive, the instinct is to widen targeting to lower CPCs. This is the wrong move. Wider targeting on LinkedIn means reaching people who are not your buyers — more impressions, lower CPCs, but worse lead quality and worse return on ad spend. Tighter targeting and higher CPCs to reach the right audience is almost always more efficient.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common LinkedIn Ads mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Not installing the Insight Tag before launch:</strong> Without it, you have no retargeting capability and no conversion data. Install it on day one.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the same creative for 3+ months:</strong> LinkedIn audience pools are small. Creative fatigue sets in fast. Plan a creative refresh cadence from the start.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring frequency:</strong> LinkedIn reports impression frequency per member. When frequency exceeds 6-8 for a campaign, pause and refresh the creative or rotate to a new audience segment.</li>
          <li><strong>Running awareness and conversion campaigns to the same audience simultaneously:</strong> This creates internal auction competition and inflated CPCs. Segment budget by funnel stage and audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Not following up on Lead Gen Form leads within 24 hours:</strong> LinkedIn lead quality degrades sharply with time. Leads submitted on Monday need a follow-up by Tuesday. Integrate Lead Gen Forms with your CRM via LinkedIn's native integrations or Zapier.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
